<p><b>Geometry</b><sup id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>a<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometr=
y#cite_note-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup> is a branch of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Mathematics" title=3D"Mathematics">mathematics</a> concerned with pr=
operties of space such as the distance, shape, size, and relative position =
of figures.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Risi2015_3-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-Risi2015-3"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> =
Geometry is, along with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic=
" title=3D"Arithmetic">arithmetic</a>, one of the oldest branches of mathem=
atics. A mathematician who works in the field of geometry is called a <i><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_geometers" title=3D"List of =
geometers">geometer</a></i>. Until the 19th century, geometry was almost ex=
clusively devoted to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_geo=
metry" title=3D"Euclidean geometry">Euclidean geometry</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometr=
y#cite_note-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>b<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup> which includes the notions of <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Point_(geometry)" title=3D"Point (geometry)">point</a=
>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Line_(geometry)" title=3D"Line =
(geometry)">line</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plane_(geome=
try)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Plane (geometry)">plane</a>, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Distance" title=3D"Distance">distance</a>=
, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Angle" title=3D"Angle">angle</a>=
, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Surface_(mathematics)" title=3D"=
Surface (mathematics)">surface</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Curve" title=3D"Curve">curve</a>, as fundamental concepts.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-Tabak_2014_xiv_5-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-Tabak_2014_xiv-5"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Originally developed to model the physical world, geometry has appli=
cations in almost all sciences, and also in art, <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Architecture" title=3D"Architecture">architecture</a>, and o=
ther activities that are related to graphics.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Meyer2006_=
6-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#=
cite_note-Meyer2006-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Geometry also has applications in areas o=
f mathematics that are apparently unrelated. For example, methods of algebr=
aic geometry are fundamental in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wi=
les%27s_proof_of_Fermat%27s_Last_Theorem" title=3D"Wiles's proof of Fermat'=
s Last Theorem">Wiles's proof</a> of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Fermat%27s_Last_Theorem" title=3D"Fermat's Last Theorem">Fermat's Last T=
heorem</a>, a problem that was stated in terms of <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Elementary_arithmetic" title=3D"Elementary arithmetic">elem=
entary arithmetic</a>, and remained unsolved for several centuries.
</p><p>During the 19th century several discoveries enlarged dramatically th=
e scope of geometry. One of the oldest such discoveries is <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carl_Friedrich_Gauss" title=3D"Carl Friedrich Gaus=
s">Carl Friedrich Gauss</a>'s <span title=3D"Latin-language text"><span lan=
g=3D"la" style=3D"font-style: normal;"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Theorema_Egregium" title=3D"Theorema Egregium">Theorema Egregium</a></=
span></span> ("remarkable theorem") that asserts roughly that the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaussian_curvature" title=3D"Gaussian cur=
vature">Gaussian curvature</a> of a surface is independent from any specifi=
c <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Embedding" title=3D"Embedding">e=
mbedding</a> in a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_space"=
 title=3D"Euclidean space">Euclidean space</a>. This implies that surfaces =
can be studied <i>intrinsically</i>, that is, as stand-alone spaces, and ha=
s been expanded into the theory of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Manifold" title=3D"Manifold">manifolds</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Riemannian_geometry" title=3D"Riemannian geometry">Riemannian=
 geometry</a>. Later in the 19th century, it appeared that geometries witho=
ut the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parallel_postulate" title=
=3D"Parallel postulate">parallel postulate</a> (<a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Non-Euclidean_geometries" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Non-=
Euclidean geometries">non-Euclidean geometries</a>) can be developed withou=
t introducing any contradiction. The geometry that underlies <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/General_relativity" title=3D"General relativity"=
>general relativity</a> is a famous application of non-Euclidean geometry.
</p><p>Since the late 19th century, the scope of geometry has been greatly =
expanded, and the field has been split in many subfields that depend on the=
 underlying methods=E2=80=94<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Differ=
ential_geometry" title=3D"Differential geometry">differential geometry</a>,=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebraic_geometry" title=3D"Alge=
braic geometry">algebraic geometry</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Computational_geometry" title=3D"Computational geometry">computationa=
l geometry</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebraic_topology=
" title=3D"Algebraic topology">algebraic topology</a>, <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Discrete_geometry" title=3D"Discrete geometry">discret=
e geometry</a> (also known as <i>combinatorial geometry</i>), etc.=E2=80=94=
or on the properties of Euclidean spaces that are disregarded=E2=80=94<a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Projective_geometry" title=3D"Projectiv=
e geometry">projective geometry</a> that consider only alignment of points =
but not distance and parallelism, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Affine_geometry" title=3D"Affine geometry">affine geometry</a> that omits t=
he concept of angle and distance, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Finite_geometry" title=3D"Finite geometry">finite geometry</a> that omits <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Continuity_(mathematics)" class=3D"=
mw-redirect" title=3D"Continuity (mathematics)">continuity</a>, and others.=
 This enlargement of the scope of geometry led to a change of meaning of th=
e word "space", which originally referred to the three-dimensional <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Space" title=3D"Space">space</a> of the p=
hysical world and its <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Model" title=
=3D"Model">model</a> provided by Euclidean geometry; presently a <b>geometr=
ic space</b>, or simply a <i>space</i> is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Mathematical_structure" title=3D"Mathematical structure">mathemat=
ical structure</a> on which some geometry is defined.
</p>
