<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_geometry"=
 title=3D"History of geometry">History of geometry</a></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Westerner_and_Arab_practicing=
_geometry_15th_century_manuscript.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img s=
rc=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/45/Westerner_a=
nd_Arab_practicing_geometry_15th_century_manuscript.jpg/250px-Westerner_and=
_Arab_practicing_geometry_15th_century_manuscript.jpg" decoding=3D"async" w=
idth=3D"250" height=3D"244" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"21=
30" data-file-height=3D"2083"></a><figcaption>A <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Ethnic_groups_in_Europe" title=3D"Ethnic groups in Europe">Eu=
ropean</a> and an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arab" class=3D"m=
w-redirect" title=3D"Arab">Arab</a> practicing geometry in the 15th century=
</figcaption></figure>
<p>The earliest recorded beginnings of geometry can be traced to ancient <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mesopotamia" title=3D"Mesopotamia">M=
esopotamia</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ancient_Egypt" =
title=3D"Ancient Egypt">Egypt</a> in the 2nd millennium BC.<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-7" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometr=
y#cite_note-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-8" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-8"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Early ge=
ometry was a collection of empirically discovered principles concerning len=
gths, angles, areas, and volumes, which were developed to meet some practic=
al need in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Surveying" title=3D"Sur=
veying">surveying</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Constructio=
n" title=3D"Construction">construction</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Astronomy" title=3D"Astronomy">astronomy</a>, and various crafts.=
 The earliest known texts on geometry are the <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Egyptian_mathematics" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Egyptian m=
athematics">Egyptian</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rhind_Mat=
hematical_Papyrus" title=3D"Rhind Mathematical Papyrus">Rhind Papyrus</a> (=
2000=E2=80=931800 BC) and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moscow_M=
athematical_Papyrus" title=3D"Moscow Mathematical Papyrus">Moscow Papyrus</=
a> (<abbr title=3D"circa">c.</abbr><span style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">=E2=
=80=891890 BC</span>), and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bab=
ylonian_mathematics" title=3D"Babylonian mathematics">Babylonian clay table=
ts</a>, such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plimpton_322" titl=
e=3D"Plimpton 322">Plimpton 322</a> (1900 BC). For example, the Moscow Papy=
rus gives a formula for calculating the volume of a truncated pyramid, or <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frustum" title=3D"Frustum">frustum<=
/a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Boyer_1991_loc=3DEgypt_p._19_9-0" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-Boyer_1991_l=
oc=3DEgypt_p._19-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Later clay tablets (350=E2=80=9350 BC) demon=
strate that Babylonian astronomers implemented <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Trapezoid" title=3D"Trapezoid">trapezoid</a> procedures for co=
mputing Jupiter's position and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dis=
placement_(vector)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Displacement (vector)">m=
otion</a> within time-velocity space. These geometric procedures anticipate=
d the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oxford_Calculators" title=3D=
"Oxford Calculators">Oxford Calculators</a>, including the <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mean_speed_theorem" title=3D"Mean speed theorem">m=
ean speed theorem</a>, by 14 centuries.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-10"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup> South of Egypt the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nubia" =
title=3D"Nubia">ancient Nubians</a> established a system of geometry includ=
ing early versions of sun clocks.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-11" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-11"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
><sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In the 7th century BC, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Greek_mathematics" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Greek mathematics">Greek<=
/a> mathematician <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thales_of_Miletu=
s" title=3D"Thales of Miletus">Thales of Miletus</a> used geometry to solve=
 problems such as calculating the height of pyramids and the distance of sh=
ips from the shore. He is credited with the first use of deductive reasonin=
g applied to geometry, by deriving four corollaries to <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thales%27s_theorem" title=3D"Thales's theorem">Thales'=
s theorem</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Boyer_1991_loc=3DIonia_and_the_Pythagorea=
ns_p._43_13-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Geometry#cite_note-Boyer_1991_loc=3DIonia_and_the_Pythagoreans_p._43-13"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pythagoras" title=3D"Py=
thagoras">Pythagoras</a> established the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Pythagoreans" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Pythagoreans">Pythagore=
an School</a>, which is credited with the first proof of the <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pythagorean_theorem" title=3D"Pythagorean theore=
m">Pythagorean theorem</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-14" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-14"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> tho=
ugh the statement of the theorem has a long history.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-15"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite=
_note-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-16" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-16"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eudoxus_of_Cnidus" title=3D"Eudoxus of Cn=
idus">Eudoxus</a> (408=E2=80=93<abbr title=3D"circa">c.</abbr><span style=
=3D"white-space:nowrap;">=E2=80=89355 BC</span>) developed the <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Method_of_exhaustion" title=3D"Method of exhau=
stion">method of exhaustion</a>, which allowed the calculation of areas and=
 volumes of curvilinear figures,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-17" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-17"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> as well as a theory of ratios that avoided the problem of <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Incommensurable_magnitudes" class=3D"mw-redirect"=
 title=3D"Incommensurable magnitudes">incommensurable magnitudes</a>, which=
 enabled subsequent geometers to make significant advances. Around 300 BC, =
geometry was revolutionized by Euclid, whose <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Euclid%27s_Elements" title=3D"Euclid's Elements">Elements</a>=
</i>, widely considered the most successful and influential textbook of all=
 time,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-18" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> introduced <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_rigor" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Mathematical rigor">mathematical rigor</a> through the <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Axiomatic_method" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"A=
xiomatic method">axiomatic method</a> and is the earliest example of the fo=
rmat still used in mathematics today, that of definition, axiom, theorem, a=
nd proof. Although most of the contents of the <i>Elements</i> were already=
 known, Euclid arranged them into a single, coherent logical framework.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-Boyer_1991_loc=3DEuclid_of_Alexandria_p._104_19-0" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-Boy=
er_1991_loc=3DEuclid_of_Alexandria_p._104-19"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The <i>Elements</=
i> was known to all educated people in the West until the middle of the 20t=
h century and its contents are still taught in geometry classes today.<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-20" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Geometry#cite_note-20"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Archimedes" title=3D"Archimedes">Archimedes</a> (<abbr title=3D"circa=
">c.</abbr><span style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">=E2=80=89287=E2=80=93212 BC<=
/span>) of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Syracuse,_Italy" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Syracuse, Italy">Syracuse, Italy</a> used the met=
hod of exhaustion to calculate the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Area" title=3D"Area">area</a> under the arc of a <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Parabola" title=3D"Parabola">parabola</a> with the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Series_(mathematics)" title=3D"Series (ma=
thematics)">summation of an infinite series</a>, and gave remarkably accura=
te approximations of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pi" title=3D"=
Pi">pi</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-21" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-21"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>19<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> He also studied the=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Archimedes_spiral" class=3D"mw-re=
direct" title=3D"Archimedes spiral">spiral</a> bearing his name and obtaine=
d formulas for the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volume" title=
=3D"Volume">volumes</a> of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Surface=
_of_revolution" title=3D"Surface of revolution">surfaces of revolution</a>.
</p>
