caption></figure>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indian_mathematics" title=3D"In=
dian mathematics">Indian</a> mathematicians also made many important contri=
butions in geometry. The <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shatap=
atha_Brahmana" title=3D"Shatapatha Brahmana">Shatapatha Brahmana</a></i> (3=
rd century BC) contains rules for ritual geometric constructions that are s=
imilar to the <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shulba_Sutras" ti=
tle=3D"Shulba Sutras">Sulba Sutras</a></i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Staal_1999_2=
2-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#=
cite_note-Staal_1999-22"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>20<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> According to (<a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#CITEREFHayashi2005">Hayashi 2005</a>, p.&nbsp;363=
), the <i>=C5=9Aulba S=C5=ABtras</i> contain "the earliest extant verbal ex=
pression of the Pythagorean Theorem in the world, although it had already b=
een known to the Old Babylonians. They contain lists of <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pythagorean_triples" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"P=
ythagorean triples">Pythagorean triples</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-23" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-=
23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>c<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup> which are particular cases of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Diophantine_equations" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Diophantin=
e equations">Diophantine equations</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-cooke198_24-0" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_n=
ote-cooke198-24"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
In the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bakhshali_manuscript" title=
=3D"Bakhshali manuscript">Bakhshali manuscript</a>, there are a handful of =
geometric problems (including problems about volumes of irregular solids). =
The Bakhshali manuscript also "employs a decimal place value system with a =
dot for zero."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-hayashi2005-371_25-0" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-hayashi2005-37=
1-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aryabhata" title=
=3D"Aryabhata">Aryabhata</a>'s <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Aryabhatiya" title=3D"Aryabhatiya">Aryabhatiya</a></i> (499) includes the c=
omputation of areas and volumes.
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brahmagupta" title=3D"Brahmagupta"=
>Brahmagupta</a> wrote his astronomical work <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Brahmasphutasiddhanta" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Brahmas=
phutasiddhanta"><span title=3D"International Alphabet of Sanskrit translite=
ration"><i lang=3D"sa-Latn">Br=C4=81hmasphu=E1=B9=ADasiddh=C4=81nta</i></sp=
an></a></i> in 628. Chapter 12, containing 66 <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Sanskrit" title=3D"Sanskrit">Sanskrit</a> verses, was divided i=
nto two sections: "basic operations" (including cube roots, fractions, rati=
o and proportion, and barter) and "practical mathematics" (including mixtur=
e, mathematical series, plane figures, stacking bricks, sawing of timber, a=
nd piling of grain).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-hayashi2003-p121-122_26-0" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-hay=
ashi2003-p121-122-26"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>23<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In the latter section, he stated his famo=
us theorem on the diagonals of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C=
yclic_quadrilateral" title=3D"Cyclic quadrilateral">cyclic quadrilateral</a=
>. Chapter 12 also included a formula for the area of a cyclic quadrilatera=
l (a generalization of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heron%27s_f=
ormula" title=3D"Heron's formula">Heron's formula</a>), as well as a comple=
te description of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rational_triangl=
e" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Rational triangle">rational triangles</a>=
 (<i>i.e.</i> triangles with rational sides and rational areas).<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-hayashi2003-p121-122_26-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-hayashi2003-p121-122-26"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p>
</p><p>In the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Middle_Ages" title=
=3D"Middle Ages">Middle Ages</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Mathematics_in_medieval_Islam" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Mathematics i=
n medieval Islam">mathematics in medieval Islam</a> contributed to the deve=
lopment of geometry, especially <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Al=
gebraic_geometry" title=3D"Algebraic geometry">algebraic geometry</a>.<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-27" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Geometry#cite_note-27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>24<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-28" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-28"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Al-Mahani" title=3D"Al-Ma=
hani">Al-Mahani</a> (b. 853) conceived the idea of reducing geometrical pro=
blems such as duplicating the cube to problems in algebra.<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-29" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometr=
y#cite_note-29"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Th%C4%=
81bit_ibn_Qurra" title=3D"Th=C4=81bit ibn Qurra">Th=C4=81bit ibn Qurra</a> =
(known as Thebit in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Latin" title=
=3D"Latin">Latin</a>) (836=E2=80=93901) dealt with <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic" title=3D"Arithmetic">arithmetic</a> operations=
 applied to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ratio" title=3D"Ratio"=
>ratios</a> of geometrical quantities, and contributed to the development o=
f <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_geometry" title=3D"Anal=
ytic geometry">analytic geometry</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-ReferenceA_30-0" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_n=
ote-ReferenceA-30"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>27<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oma=
r_Khayyam" title=3D"Omar Khayyam">Omar Khayyam</a> (1048=E2=80=931131) foun=
d geometric solutions to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cubic_equ=
ation" title=3D"Cubic equation">cubic equations</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-31"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite=
_note-31"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>28<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup> The theorems of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Ibn_al-Haytham" title=3D"Ibn al-Haytham">Ibn al-Haytham</a> (Alhazen), =
Omar Khayyam and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nasir_al-Din_al-T=
usi" title=3D"Nasir al-Din al-Tusi">Nasir al-Din al-Tusi</a> on <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quadrilateral" title=3D"Quadrilateral">quadri=
laterals</a>, including the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lamber=
t_quadrilateral" title=3D"Lambert quadrilateral">Lambert quadrilateral</a> =
and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saccheri_quadrilateral" title=
=3D"Saccheri quadrilateral">Saccheri quadrilateral</a>, were part of a line=
 of research on the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parallel_postu=
late" title=3D"Parallel postulate">parallel postulate</a> continued by late=
r European geometers, including <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vi=
tello" title=3D"Vitello">Vitello</a> (<abbr title=3D"circa">c.</abbr><span =
style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">=E2=80=891230</span>&nbsp;=E2=80=93 c.<span s=
tyle=3D"white-space:nowrap;">=E2=80=891314</span>), <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Gersonides" title=3D"Gersonides">Gersonides</a> (1288=E2=
=80=931344), Alfonso, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Wallis"=
 title=3D"John Wallis">John Wallis</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Giovanni_Girolamo_Saccheri" title=3D"Giovanni Girolamo Saccheri">=
Giovanni Girolamo Saccheri</a>, that by the 19th century led to the discove=
ry of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperbolic_geometry" title=
=3D"Hyperbolic geometry">hyperbolic geometry</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-32" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_no=
te-32"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>29<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In the early 17th century, there were two important developments in =
geometry. The first was the creation of analytic geometry, or geometry with=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coordinate_system" title=3D"Coord=
inate system">coordinates</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Equation" title=3D"Equation">equations</a>, by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Ren%C3%A9_Descartes" title=3D"Ren=C3=A9 Descartes">Ren=C3=A9 D=
escartes</a> (1596=E2=80=931650) and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Pierre_de_Fermat" title=3D"Pierre de Fermat">Pierre de Fermat</a> (1601=
=E2=80=931665).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Boyer2012_33-0" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-Boyer2012-33"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>30<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup> This was a necessary precursor to the development of <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus" title=3D"Calculus">calculus</a> and a p=
recise quantitative science of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phy=
sics" title=3D"Physics">physics</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Edwards2012_34-0" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_n=
ote-Edwards2012-34"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>31<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The second geometric development of this pe=
riod was the systematic study of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P=
rojective_geometry" title=3D"Projective geometry">projective geometry</a> b=
y <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Girard_Desargues" title=3D"Girar=
d Desargues">Girard Desargues</a> (1591=E2=80=931661).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-F=
ieldGray2012_35-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Geometry#cite_note-FieldGray2012-35"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>32<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Projective geometry s=
tudies properties of shapes which are unchanged under <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Projection_(linear_algebra)" title=3D"Projection (linea=
r algebra)">projections</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Se=
ction_(fiber_bundle)" title=3D"Section (fiber bundle)">sections</a>, especi=
ally as they relate to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Perspective=
_(graphical)" title=3D"Perspective (graphical)">artistic perspective</a>.<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-Wylie2011_36-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-Wylie2011-36"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>33<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Two developments in geometry in the 19th century changed the way it =
had been studied previously.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Gray2011_37-0" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-Gray201=
1-37"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>34<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup> These were the discovery of <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Non-Euclidean_geometry" title=3D"Non-Euclidean geometry">non-Eu=
clidean geometries</a> by Nikolai Ivanovich Lobachevsky, J=C3=A1nos Bolyai =
and Carl Friedrich Gauss and of the formulation of <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Symmetry" title=3D"Symmetry">symmetry</a> as the central c=
onsideration in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Erlangen_progr=
amme" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Erlangen programme">Erlangen programme=
</a> of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Felix_Klein" title=3D"Feli=
x Klein">Felix Klein</a> (which generalized the Euclidean and non-Euclidean=
 geometries). Two of the master geometers of the time were <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bernhard_Riemann" title=3D"Bernhard Riemann">Bernh=
ard Riemann</a> (1826=E2=80=931866), working primarily with tools from <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_analysis" title=3D"Mathem=
atical analysis">mathematical analysis</a>, and introducing the <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Riemann_surface" title=3D"Riemann surface">Ri=
emann surface</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henri_Poinc=
ar%C3%A9" title=3D"Henri Poincar=C3=A9">Henri Poincar=C3=A9</a>, the founde=
r of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebraic_topology" title=3D"=
Algebraic topology">algebraic topology</a> and the geometric theory of <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dynamical_system" title=3D"Dynamical s=
ystem">dynamical systems</a>. As a consequence of these major changes in th=
e conception of geometry, the concept of "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Space_(mathematics)" title=3D"Space (mathematics)">space</a>" becam=
e something rich and varied, and the natural background for theories as dif=
ferent as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_analysis" title=
=3D"Complex analysis">complex analysis</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Classical_mechanics" title=3D"Classical mechanics">classical m=
echanics</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Bayro-Corrochano2018_38-0" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-Bayro-Corr=
ochano2018-38"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>35<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Main_concepts">Main concept=
s</h2></div>
<p>The following are some of the most important concepts in geometry.<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-Tabak_2014_xiv_5-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-Tabak_2014_xiv-5"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-Kline1990_39-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-Kline1990-39"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>36<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Axioms">Axioms</h3></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Parallel_postulate_en.svg" cl=
ass=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipe=
dia/commons/thumb/e/ed/Parallel_postulate_en.svg/250px-Parallel_postulate_e=
n.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"188" class=3D"mw-file=
-element" data-file-width=3D"800" data-file-height=3D"600"></a><figcaption>=
An illustration of Euclid's <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parall=
el_postulate" title=3D"Parallel postulate">parallel postulate</a></figcapti=
on></figure>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_geometry" titl=
e=3D"Euclidean geometry">Euclidean geometry</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Axiom" title=3D"Axiom">Axiom</a></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclid" title=3D"Euclid">Euclid=
</a> took an abstract approach to geometry in his <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Euclid%27s_Elements" title=3D"Euclid's Elements">Elements</=
a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Katz2000_40-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-Katz2000-40"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>37<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> one of =
the most influential books ever written.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Berlinski2014_4=
1-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#=
cite_note-Berlinski2014-41"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>38<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Euclid introduced certain <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Axiom" title=3D"Axiom">axioms</a>, or <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Postulate" class=3D"mw-redirect" titl=
e=3D"Postulate">postulates</a>, expressing primary or self-evident properti=
es of points, lines, and planes.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Hartshorne2013_42-0" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_no=
te-Hartshorne2013-42"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>39<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> He proceeded to rigorously deduce other p=
roperties by mathematical reasoning. The characteristic feature of Euclid's=
 approach to geometry was its rigor, and it has come to be known as <i>axio=
matic</i> or <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Synthetic_geometry=
" title=3D"Synthetic geometry">synthetic</a></i> geometry.<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-HerbstFujita2017_43-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-HerbstFujita2017-43"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>40<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> At the star=
t of the 19th century, the discovery of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Non-Euclidean_geometries" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Non-Euclidea=
n geometries">non-Euclidean geometries</a> by <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Nikolai_Ivanovich_Lobachevsky" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"N=
ikolai Ivanovich Lobachevsky">Nikolai Ivanovich Lobachevsky</a> (1792=E2=80=
=931856), <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J%C3%A1nos_Bolyai" title=
=3D"J=C3=A1nos Bolyai">J=C3=A1nos Bolyai</a> (1802=E2=80=931860), <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carl_Friedrich_Gauss" title=3D"Carl Fried=
rich Gauss">Carl Friedrich Gauss</a> (1777=E2=80=931855) and others<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-Yaglom2012_44-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-Yaglom2012-44"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>41<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> led to a revi=
val of interest in this discipline, and in the 20th century, <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Hilbert" title=3D"David Hilbert">David Hil=
bert</a> (1862=E2=80=931943) employed axiomatic reasoning in an attempt to =
provide a modern foundation of geometry.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Holme2010_45-0"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite=
_note-Holme2010-45"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>42<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Spaces_and_subspaces">Space=
s and subspaces</h3></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Points">Points</h4></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Point_(geometry)" ti=
tle=3D"Point (geometry)">Point (geometry)</a></div>
<p>Points are generally considered fundamental objects for building geometr=
y. They may be defined by the properties that they must have, as in Euclid'=
s definition as "that which has no part",<sup id=3D"cite_ref-EuclidAll_46-0=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cit=
e_note-EuclidAll-46"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>43<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> or in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Synthetic_geometry" title=3D"Synthetic geometry">synthetic geometry</a=
>. In modern mathematics, they are generally defined as <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Element_(set_theory)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"=
Element (set theory)">elements</a> of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Set_(mathematics)" title=3D"Set (mathematics)">set</a> called <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Space_(mathematics)" title=3D"Space (math=
ematics)">space</a>, which is itself <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Axiomatically" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Axiomatically">axiomatical=
ly</a> defined.
</p><p>With these modern definitions, every geometric shape is defined as a=
 set of points; this is not the case in synthetic geometry, where a line is=
 another fundamental object that is not viewed as the set of the points thr=
ough which it passes.
</p><p>However, there are modern geometries in which points are not primiti=
ve objects, or even without points.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-47" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-47"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>44<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-48" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-48"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4=
5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> One of the oldest such geo=
metries is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Whitehead%27s_point-fre=
e_geometry" title=3D"Whitehead's point-free geometry">Whitehead's point-fre=
e geometry</a>, formulated by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alfr=
ed_North_Whitehead" title=3D"Alfred North Whitehead">Alfred North Whitehead=
</a> in 1919=E2=80=931920.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Lines">Lines</h4></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Line_(geometry)" tit=
le=3D"Line (geometry)">Line (geometry)</a></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclid" title=3D"Euclid">Euclid=
</a> described a line as "breadthless length" which "lies equally with resp=
ect to the points on itself".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-EuclidAll_46-1" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-Eucli=
dAll-46"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>43<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup> In modern mathematics, given the multitude of geometri=
es, the concept of a line is closely tied to the way the geometry is descri=
bed. For instance, in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_geo=
metry" title=3D"Analytic geometry">analytic geometry</a>, a line in the pla=
ne is often defined as the set of points whose coordinates satisfy a given =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_equation" title=3D"Linear e=
quation">linear equation</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-49" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-49"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>46<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 but in a more abstract setting, such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Incidence_geometry" title=3D"Incidence geometry">incidence geometry<=
/a>, a line may be an independent object, distinct from the set of points w=
hich lie on it.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-50" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-50"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>47<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In differential=
 geometry, a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geodesic" title=3D"Ge=
odesic">geodesic</a> is a generalization of the notion of a line to <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Manifold" title=3D"Manifold">curved space=
s</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-51" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-51"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>48<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Planes">Planes</h4></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_plane" tit=
le=3D"Euclidean plane">Euclidean plane</a></div>
<p>In Euclidean geometry a plane is a flat, two-dimensional surface that ex=
tends infinitely;<sup id=3D"cite_ref-EuclidAll_46-2" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-EuclidAll-46"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>43<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup> the definitions for other types of geometries are generalizations =
of that. Planes are used in many areas of geometry. For instance, planes ca=
n be studied as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Surface_(topolog=
y)" title=3D"Surface (topology)">topological surface</a> without reference =
to distances or angles;<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Munkres_52-0" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-Munkres-52"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>49<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup> it can be studied as an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Affine_space" title=3D"Affine space">affine space</a>, where collinearity =
and ratios can be studied but not distances;<sup id=3D"cite_ref-53" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-=
53"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>50<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup> it can be studied as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Complex_plane" title=3D"Complex plane">complex plane</a> using techn=
iques of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_analysis" title=
=3D"Complex analysis">complex analysis</a>;<sup id=3D"cite_ref-54" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-54"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>51<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup> and so on.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Curves">Curves</h4></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Curve_(geometry)" cl=
ass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Curve (geometry)">Curve (geometry)</a></div>
<p>A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Curve_(geometry)" class=3D"mw=
-redirect" title=3D"Curve (geometry)">curve</a> is a 1-dimensional object t=
hat may be straight (like a line) or not; curves in 2-dimensional space are=
 called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plane_curve" title=3D"Plan=
e curve">plane curves</a> and those in 3-dimensional space are called <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Space_curve" class=3D"mw-redirect" titl=
e=3D"Space curve">space curves</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-55" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-55"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>52<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup>
</p><p>In topology, a curve is defined by a function from an interval of th=
e real numbers to another space.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Munkres_52-1" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-Munk=
res-52"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>49<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup> In differential geometry, the same definition is used, =
but the defining function is required to be differentiable.<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-Carmo_56-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Geometry#cite_note-Carmo-56"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>53<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Algebraic geometry studies <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebraic_curve" title=3D"Algebraic cur=
ve">algebraic curves</a>, which are defined as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Algebraic_varieties" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Algebraic =
varieties">algebraic varieties</a> of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Dimension_of_an_algebraic_variety" title=3D"Dimension of an algebraic v=
ariety">dimension</a> one.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-mumford_57-0" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-mumford-57=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>54<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Surfaces">Surfaces</h4></di=
v>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Surface_(mathematics=
)" title=3D"Surface (mathematics)">Surface (mathematics)</a></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Sphere_wireframe.svg" class=3D"mw-file-descri=
ption"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0=
8/Sphere_wireframe.svg/250px-Sphere_wireframe.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" w=
idth=3D"210" height=3D"210" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"40=
0" data-file-height=3D"400"></a><figcaption>A sphere is a surface that can =
be defined parametrically (by <span class=3D"nowrap"><i>x</i> =3D <i>r</i> =
sin <i>=CE=B8</i> cos <i>=CF=86</i>,</span> <span class=3D"nowrap"><i>y</i>=
 =3D <i>r</i> sin <i>=CE=B8</i> sin <i>=CF=86</i>,</span> <span class=3D"no=
wrap"><i>z</i> =3D <i>r</i> cos <i>=CE=B8</i>)</span> or implicitly (by <sp=
an class=3D"nowrap"><i>x</i><sup>2</sup> + <i>y</i><sup>2</sup> + <i>z</i><=
sup>2</sup> =E2=88=92 <i>r</i><sup>2</sup> =3D 0</span>).</figcaption></fig=
ure>
<p>A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Surface_(mathematics)" title=
=3D"Surface (mathematics)">surface</a> is a two-dimensional object, such as=
 a sphere or paraboloid.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-58" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-58"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>55<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Differential_geometry" title=3D"Diffe=
rential geometry">differential geometry</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Carmo_56-1" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_=
note-Carmo-56"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>53<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Top=
ology" title=3D"Topology">topology</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Munkres_52-2" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_no=
te-Munkres-52"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>49<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup> surfaces are described by two-dimensional 'patch=
es' (or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neighborhood_(topology)" c=
lass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Neighborhood (topology)">neighborhoods</a>) t=
hat are assembled by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diffeomorphis=
m" title=3D"Diffeomorphism">diffeomorphisms</a> or <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Homeomorphism" title=3D"Homeomorphism">homeomorphisms</a>,=
 respectively. In algebraic geometry, surfaces are described by <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polynomial_equation" class=3D"mw-redirect" ti=
tle=3D"Polynomial equation">polynomial equations</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-mu=
mford_57-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ge=
ometry#cite_note-mumford-57"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>54<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Solids">Solids</h4></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Solid_geometry" titl=
e=3D"Solid geometry">Solid geometry</a></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-left" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Blue_ball.png" class=3D"mw-fil=
e-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/c=
/cf/Blue_ball.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"95" height=3D"94" class=3D"m=
w-file-element" data-file-width=3D"95" data-file-height=3D"94"></a><figcapt=
ion>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_space" title=3D"E=
uclidean space">Euclidean space</a>, a ball is the volume bounded by a sphe=
re.</figcaption></figure>
<p>A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Solid_(mathematics)" class=3D=
"mw-redirect" title=3D"Solid (mathematics)">solid</a> is a three-dimensiona=
l object bounded by a closed surface; for example, a <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Ball_(mathematics)" title=3D"Ball (mathematics)">ball</a=
> is the volume bounded by a sphere.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Manifolds">Manifolds</h4></=
div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Manifold" title=3D"M=
anifold">Manifold</a></div>
<p>A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Manifold" title=3D"Manifold">=
manifold</a> is a generalization of the concepts of curve and surface. In <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Topology" title=3D"Topology">topolo=
gy</a>, a manifold is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Topologica=
l_space" title=3D"Topological space">topological space</a> where every poin=
t has a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neighborhood_(topology)" c=
lass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Neighborhood (topology)">neighborhood</a> tha=
t is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Homeomorphism" title=3D"Homeo=
morphism">homeomorphic</a> to Euclidean space.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Munkres_5=
2-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#=
cite_note-Munkres-52"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>49<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Differential_geometry" title=3D"Differential geometry">differential geom=
etry</a>, a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Differentiable_manifol=
d" title=3D"Differentiable manifold">differentiable manifold</a> is a space=
 where each neighborhood is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diffeo=
morphism" title=3D"Diffeomorphism">diffeomorphic</a> to Euclidean space.<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-Carmo_56-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-Carmo-56"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>53<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Manifolds are used extensively in physics, including in <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/General_relativity" title=3D"General relativit=
y">general relativity</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stri=
ng_theory" title=3D"String theory">string theory</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-59=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cit=
e_note-59"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>56<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Angles">Angles</h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Angle" title=3D"Angl=
e">Angle</a></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Angle_obtuse_acute_straight.svg" class=3D"mw-=
file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/common=
s/thumb/e/ee/Angle_obtuse_acute_straight.svg/250px-Angle_obtuse_acute_strai=
ght.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"139" class=3D"mw-fi=
le-element" data-file-width=3D"800" data-file-height=3D"445"></a><figcaptio=
n>Acute (a), obtuse (b), and straight (c) angles. The acute and obtuse angl=
es are also known as oblique angles.</figcaption></figure>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclid" title=3D"Euclid">Euclid=
</a> defines a plane angle as the inclination to each other, in a plane, of=
 two lines which meet each other, and do not lie straight with respect to e=
ach other.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-EuclidAll_46-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-EuclidAll-46"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>43<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up> In modern terms, an angle is the figure formed by two <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ray_(geometry)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ray =
(geometry)">rays</a>, called the <i>sides</i> of the angle, sharing a commo=
n endpoint, called the <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vertex_(=
geometry)" title=3D"Vertex (geometry)">vertex</a></i> of the angle.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-60" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Geometry#cite_note-60"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>57<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
The size of an angle is formalized as an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Angular_measure" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Angular measure">ang=
ular measure</a>.
</p><p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_geometry" titl=
e=3D"Euclidean geometry">Euclidean geometry</a>, angles are used to study <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polygon" title=3D"Polygon">polygons=
</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Triangle" title=3D"Triang=
le">triangles</a>, as well as forming an object of study in their own right=
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-EuclidAll_46-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-EuclidAll-46"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>43<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The stu=
dy of the angles of a triangle or of angles in a <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Unit_circle" title=3D"Unit circle">unit circle</a> forms the=
 basis of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trigonometry" title=3D"T=
rigonometry">trigonometry</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-61" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-61"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>58<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Differential_geometry" t=
itle=3D"Differential geometry">differential geometry</a> and <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus" title=3D"Calculus">calculus</a>, the a=
ngles between <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plane_curve" title=
=3D"Plane curve">plane curves</a> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Space_curve" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Space curve">space curves</a=
> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Surface_(geometry)" class=3D"=
mw-redirect" title=3D"Surface (geometry)">surfaces</a> can be calculated us=
ing the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Derivative_(calculus)" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Derivative (calculus)">derivative</a>.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-Stewart_62-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-Stewart-62"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>59<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
63" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#c=
ite_note-63"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>60<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Measures:_length,_area,_and=
_volume"><span id=3D"Measures:_length.2C_area.2C_and_volume"></span>Measure=
s: length, area, and volume<span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"Measures"></span></=
h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main articles: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Length" title=3D"Le=
ngth">Length</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area" title=3D"A=
rea">Area</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volume" title=
=3D"Volume">Volume</a></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area#List_of_formulas" t=
itle=3D"Area">Area =C2=A7&nbsp;List of formulas</a>, and <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volume#Volume_formulas" title=3D"Volume">Volume =C2=
=A7&nbsp;Volume formulas</a></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Length" title=3D"Length">Length=
</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area" title=3D"Area">area</a=
>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volume" title=3D"Volume">vo=
lume</a> describe the size or extent of an object in one dimension, two dim=
ension, and three dimensions respectively.
</p><p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_geometry" titl=
e=3D"Euclidean geometry">Euclidean geometry</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_geometry" title=3D"Analytic geometry">analytic g=
eometry</a>, the length of a line segment can often be calculated by the <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pythagorean_theorem" title=3D"Pythag=
orean theorem">Pythagorean theorem</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Cannon2017_64-0"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite=
_note-Cannon2017-64"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>61<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Area and volume can be defined as fundamental quantities separate fr=
om length, or they can be described and calculated in terms of lengths in a=
 plane or 3-dimensional space. Mathematicians have found many explicit <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area#List_of_formulas" title=3D"Area">=
formulas for area</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volume#F=
ormulas" title=3D"Volume">formulas for volume</a> of various geometric obje=
cts. In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus" title=3D"Calculu=
s">calculus</a>, area and volume can be defined in terms of <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integral" title=3D"Integral">integrals</a>, such =
as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Riemann_integral" title=3D"=
Riemann integral">Riemann integral</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Strang1991_65-0" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_=
note-Strang1991-65"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>62<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> or the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Lebesgue_integral" title=3D"Lebesgue integral">Lebesgue integral</a>.<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-Bear2002_66-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-Bear2002-66"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>63<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Other geometrical measures include the <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Curvature" title=3D"Curvature">curvature</a> and <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Compactness_measure" title=3D"Compactness measur=
e">compactness</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Metrics_and_measures">Metri=
cs and measures</h4></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main articles: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metric_(mathematics=
)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Metric (mathematics)">Metric (mathematics=
)</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Measure_(mathematics)" t=
itle=3D"Measure (mathematics)">Measure (mathematics)</a></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Chinese_pythagoras.jpg" class=
=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia=
/commons/thumb/c/c3/Chinese_pythagoras.jpg/250px-Chinese_pythagoras.jpg" de=
coding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"136" class=3D"mw-file-element" dat=
a-file-width=3D"871" data-file-height=3D"475"></a><figcaption>Visual checki=
ng of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pythagorean_theorem" tit=
le=3D"Pythagorean theorem">Pythagorean theorem</a> for the (3, 4, 5) <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Triangle" title=3D"Triangle">triangle</a=
> as in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zhoubi_Suanjing" title=
=3D"Zhoubi Suanjing">Zhoubi Suanjing</a> 500=E2=80=93200&nbsp;BC. The Pytha=
gorean theorem is a consequence of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Euclidean_metric" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Euclidean metric">Euc=
lidean metric</a>.</figcaption></figure>
<p>The concept of length or distance can be generalized, leading to the ide=
a of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metric_space" title=3D"Metric=
 space">metrics</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-67" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-67"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>64<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> For instan=
ce, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_metric" class=3D=
"mw-redirect" title=3D"Euclidean metric">Euclidean metric</a> measures the =
distance between points in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euc=
lidean_plane" title=3D"Euclidean plane">Euclidean plane</a>, while the <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperbolic_metric" class=3D"mw-redirec=
t" title=3D"Hyperbolic metric">hyperbolic metric</a> measures the distance =
in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperbolic_plane" class=3D"=
mw-redirect" title=3D"Hyperbolic plane">hyperbolic plane</a>. Other importa=
nt examples of metrics include the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Lorentz_metric" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Lorentz metric">Lorentz met=
ric</a> of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special_relativity" tit=
le=3D"Special relativity">special relativity</a> and the semi-<a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Riemannian_metric" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Riemannian metric">Riemannian metrics</a> of <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/General_relativity" title=3D"General relativity">general rel=
ativity</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-68" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-68"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>65<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In a different direction, the concepts of length, area and volume ar=
e extended by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Measure_theory" clas=
s=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Measure theory">measure theory</a>, which studie=
s methods of assigning a size or <i>measure</i> to <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Set_(mathematics)" title=3D"Set (mathematics)">sets</a>, w=
here the measures follow rules similar to those of classical area and volum=
e.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Tao2011_69-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-Tao2011-69"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>66<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Congruence_and_similarity">=
Congruence and similarity</h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main articles: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Congruence_(geometr=
y)" title=3D"Congruence (geometry)">Congruence (geometry)</a> and <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Similarity_(geometry)" title=3D"Similarit=
y (geometry)">Similarity (geometry)</a></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Congruence_(geometry)" title=3D=
"Congruence (geometry)">Congruence</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Similarity_(geometry)" title=3D"Similarity (geometry)">similarity<=
/a> are concepts that describe when two shapes have similar characteristics=
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Libeskind2008_70-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-Libeskind2008-70"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>67<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 In Euclidean geometry, similarity is used to describe objects that have th=
e same shape, while congruence is used to describe objects that are the sam=
e in both size and shape.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Freitag2013_71-0" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-Freitag=
2013-71"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>68<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hilbert" clas=
s=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Hilbert">Hilbert</a>, in his work on creating a =
more rigorous foundation for geometry, treated congruence as an undefined t=
erm whose properties are defined by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Axiom" title=3D"Axiom">axioms</a>.
</p><p>Congruence and similarity are generalized in <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Transformation_geometry" title=3D"Transformation geometry=
">transformation geometry</a>, which studies the properties of geometric ob=
jects that are preserved by different kinds of transformations.<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-Martin2012_72-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-Martin2012-72"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>69<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Compass_and_straightedge_co=
nstructions">Compass and straightedge constructions</h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Compass_and_straight=
edge_constructions" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Compass and straightedge=
 constructions">Compass and straightedge constructions</a></div>
<p>Classical geometers paid special attention to constructing geometric obj=
ects that had been described in some other way. Classically, the only instr=
uments used in most geometric constructions are the <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Compass_(drafting)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Compas=
s (drafting)">compass</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rule=
r" title=3D"Ruler">straightedge</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-73" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-73"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>d<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup> Also, every construction had to be complete in a finite number of step=
s. However, some problems turned out to be difficult or impossible to solve=
 by these means alone, and ingenious constructions using <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neusis_construction" title=3D"Neusis construction">n=
eusis</a>, parabolas and other curves, or mechanical devices, were found.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Rotation_and_orientation">R=
otation and orientation</h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main articles: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rotation_(geometry)=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Rotation (geometry)">Rotation (geometry)</=
a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orientation_(geometry)" tit=
le=3D"Orientation (geometry)">Orientation (geometry)</a></div>
<p>The geometrical concepts of rotation and orientation define part of the =
placement of objects embedded in the plane or in space.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Dimension">Dimension</h3></=
div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
For broader coverage of this topic, see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Dimension_(mathematics)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Dimension (ma=
thematics)">Dimension (mathematics)</a>.</div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Von_Koch_curve.gif" class=3D"mw-file-descript=
ion"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fd/=
Von_Koch_curve.gif/250px-Von_Koch_curve.gif" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"25=
0" height=3D"260" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"300" data-fi=
le-height=3D"312"></a><figcaption>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Koch_snowflake" title=3D"Koch snowflake">Koch snowflake</a>, with <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fractal_dimension" title=3D"Fractal dim=
ension">fractal dimension</a>=3Dlog4/log3 and <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Topological_dimension" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Topologic=
al dimension">topological dimension</a>=3D1</figcaption></figure>
<p>Traditional geometry allowed dimensions 1 (a <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Line_(geometry)" title=3D"Line (geometry)">line</a> or curve)=
, 2 (a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plane_(mathematics)" title=
=3D"Plane (mathematics)">plane</a> or surface), and 3 (our ambient world co=
nceived of as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Three-dimensional_sp=
ace" title=3D"Three-dimensional space">three-dimensional space</a>). Furthe=
rmore, mathematicians and physicists have used <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Higher_dimension" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Higher dimens=
ion">higher dimensions</a> for nearly two centuries.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Bla=
cklock2018_74-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Geometry#cite_note-Blacklock2018-74"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>70<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> One example of a mathem=
atical use for higher dimensions is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Configuration_space_(physics)" title=3D"Configuration space (physics)=
">configuration space</a> of a physical system, which has a dimension equal=
 to the system's <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Degrees_of_freedo=
m" title=3D"Degrees of freedom">degrees of freedom</a>. For instance, the c=
onfiguration of a screw can be described by five coordinates.<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-Joly1895_75-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-Joly1895-75"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>71<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/General_topology" title=
=3D"General topology">general topology</a>, the concept of dimension has be=
en extended from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Natural_number" t=
itle=3D"Natural number">natural numbers</a>, to infinite dimension (<a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hilbert_space" title=3D"Hilbert space">Hi=
lbert spaces</a>, for example) and positive <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Real_number" title=3D"Real number">real numbers</a> (in <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fractal_geometry" class=3D"mw-redirect" t=
itle=3D"Fractal geometry">fractal geometry</a>).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Temam20=
13_76-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geome=
try#cite_note-Temam2013-76"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>72<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Algebraic_geometry" title=3D"Algebraic geometry">algebraic geometr=
y</a>, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dimension_of_an_algebra=
ic_variety" title=3D"Dimension of an algebraic variety">dimension of an alg=
ebraic variety</a> has received a number of apparently different definition=
s, which are all equivalent in the most common cases.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Ja=
cobLam1994_77-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Geometry#cite_note-JacobLam1994-77"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>73<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Symmetry">Symmetry</h3></di=
v>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Symmetry" title=3D"S=
ymmetry">Symmetry</a></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Order-3_heptakis_heptagonal_t=
iling.png" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimed=
ia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e6/Order-3_heptakis_heptagonal_tiling.png/=
250px-Order-3_heptakis_heptagonal_tiling.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"2=
50" height=3D"250" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"800" data-f=
ile-height=3D"800"></a><figcaption>A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Order-3_bisected_heptagonal_tiling" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Order=
-3 bisected heptagonal tiling">tiling</a> of the <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Hyperbolic_geometry" title=3D"Hyperbolic geometry">hyperboli=
c plane</a></figcaption></figure>
<p>The theme of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Symmetry" title=3D=
"Symmetry">symmetry</a> in geometry is nearly as old as the science of geom=
etry itself.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Stewart2008_78-0" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-Stewart2008-78"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>74<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup> Symmetric shapes such as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Circle" title=3D"Circle">circle</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Regular_polygon" title=3D"Regular polygon">regular polygons</a> and <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Platonic_solid" title=3D"Platonic s=
olid">platonic solids</a> held deep significance for many ancient philosoph=
ers<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Alexey2009_79-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-Alexey2009-79"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>75<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and=
 were investigated in detail before the time of Euclid.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
Hartshorne2013_42-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-Hartshorne2013-42"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>39<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Symmetric patterns=
 occur in nature and were artistically rendered in a multitude of forms, in=
cluding the graphics of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leonardo_d=
a_Vinci" title=3D"Leonardo da Vinci">Leonardo da Vinci</a>, <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M._C._Escher" title=3D"M. C. Escher">M. C. Escher=
</a>, and others.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Hahn1998_80-0" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-Hahn1998-80"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>76<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup> In the second half of the 19th century, the relationship between sym=
metry and geometry came under intense scrutiny. <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Felix_Klein" title=3D"Felix Klein">Felix Klein</a>'s <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Erlangen_program" title=3D"Erlangen progr=
am">Erlangen program</a> proclaimed that, in a very precise sense, symmetry=
, expressed via the notion of a transformation <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Group_(mathematics)" title=3D"Group (mathematics)">group</a>, =
determines what geometry <i>is</i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Cantwell2002_81-0" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_n=
ote-Cantwell2002-81"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>77<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Symmetry in classical <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_geometry" title=3D"Euclidean geometry">Eucli=
dean geometry</a> is represented by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Congruence_(geometry)" title=3D"Congruence (geometry)">congruences</a> an=
d rigid motions, whereas in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Projec=
tive_geometry" title=3D"Projective geometry">projective geometry</a> an ana=
logous role is played by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Collineat=
ion" title=3D"Collineation">collineations</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Geometric_transformation" title=3D"Geometric transformation">g=
eometric transformations</a> that take straight lines into straight lines.<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-RosenfeldWiebe2013_82-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-RosenfeldWiebe2013-82"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>78<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup> However it was in the new geometries of Bolyai and Lobachevsky, Ri=
emann, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Kingdon_Clifford" t=
itle=3D"William Kingdon Clifford">Clifford</a> and Klein, and <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sophus_Lie" title=3D"Sophus Lie">Sophus Lie</a>=
 that Klein's idea to 'define a geometry via its <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Symmetry_group" title=3D"Symmetry group">symmetry group</a>'=
 found its inspiration.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Pesic2007_83-0" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-Pesic2007-8=
3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>79<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup> Both discrete and continuous symmetries play prominent roles=
 in geometry, the former in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Topolo=
gy" title=3D"Topology">topology</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Geometric_group_theory" title=3D"Geometric group theory">geometric gr=
oup theory</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Kaku2012_84-0" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-Kaku2012-84"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>80<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-BestvinaSageev2014_85-0" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-BestvinaSageev2014-85=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>81<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup> the latter in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lie_th=
eory" title=3D"Lie theory">Lie theory</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Riemannian_geometry" title=3D"Riemannian geometry">Riemannian g=
eometry</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Steeb1996_86-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-Steeb1996-86"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>82<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Misner2005_87-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-Misner2005-87"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>83<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>A different type of symmetry is the principle of <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Duality_(projective_geometry)" title=3D"Duality (proj=
ective geometry)">duality</a> in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P=
rojective_geometry" title=3D"Projective geometry">projective geometry</a>, =
among other fields. This meta-phenomenon can roughly be described as follow=
s: in any <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Theorem" title=3D"Theore=
m">theorem</a>, exchange <i>point</i> with <i>plane</i>, <i>join</i> with <=
i>meet</i>, <i>lies in</i> with <i>contains</i>, and the result is an equal=
ly true theorem.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Dowling1917_88-0" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-Dowling1917-88">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>84<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup> A similar and closely related form of duality exists between a =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vector_space" title=3D"Vector spac=
e">vector space</a> and its <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dual_s=
pace" title=3D"Dual space">dual space</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Gierz2006_89-=
0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#ci=
te_note-Gierz2006-89"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>85<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Contemporary_geometry">Cont=
emporary geometry</h2></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Euclidean_geometry">Euclide=
an geometry</h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_geometry" =
title=3D"Euclidean geometry">Euclidean geometry</a></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_geometry" title=3D"Eu=
clidean geometry">Euclidean geometry</a> is geometry in its classical sense=
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-ButtsBrown2012_90-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-ButtsBrown2012-90"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>86<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p> As it models the space of the physical world, it is used in many scienti=
fic areas, such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mechanics" titl=
e=3D"Mechanics">mechanics</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ast=
ronomy" title=3D"Astronomy">astronomy</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Crystallography" title=3D"Crystallography">crystallography</a>,<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-91" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-91"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>87<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and many technical fields, such a=
s <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Engineering" title=3D"Engineerin=
g">engineering</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Abbot2013_92-0" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-Abbot2013-92"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>88<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Architecture" title=3D"=
Architecture">architecture</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-HerseyHersey2001_93-0" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_n=
ote-HerseyHersey2001-93"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>89<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Geodesy" title=3D"Geodesy">geodesy</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Van=C3=ADcekK=
rakiwsky2015_94-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Geometry#cite_note-Van%C3%ADcekKrakiwsky2015-94"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>90<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aerodynamics" title=3D"Aerodynamics">aero=
dynamics</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-CummingsMorton2015_95-0" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-CummingsMort=
on2015-95"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>91<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Navigat=
ion" title=3D"Navigation">navigation</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Williams1998_9=
6-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#=
cite_note-Williams1998-96"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>92<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The mandatory educational curriculum=
 of the majority of nations includes the study of Euclidean concepts such a=
s <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Point_(geometry)" title=3D"Point=
 (geometry)">points</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Line_(geo=
metry)" title=3D"Line (geometry)">lines</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Plane_(mathematics)" title=3D"Plane (mathematics)">planes</a>, <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Angle" title=3D"Angle">angles</a>, =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Triangle" title=3D"Triangle">trian=
gles</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Congruence_(geometry)" t=
itle=3D"Congruence (geometry)">congruence</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Similarity_(geometry)" title=3D"Similarity (geometry)">similar=
ity</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Solid_figure" class=3D"mw=
-redirect" title=3D"Solid figure">solid figures</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Circle" title=3D"Circle">circles</a>, and <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_geometry" title=3D"Analytic geometry">a=
nalytic geometry</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Schmidt,_W._2002_97-0" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-Schmid=
t,_W._2002-97"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>93<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Euclidean_vectors">Euclidea=
n vectors</h4></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_vector" ti=
tle=3D"Euclidean vector">Euclidean vector</a></div>
<p>Euclidean vectors are used for a myriad of applications in physics and e=
ngineering, such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Position_(geom=
etry)" title=3D"Position (geometry)">position</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Displacement_(geometry)" title=3D"Displacement (geometry)"=
>displacement</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deformation_(ph=
ysics)" title=3D"Deformation (physics)">deformation</a>, <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Velocity" title=3D"Velocity">velocity</a>, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Acceleration" title=3D"Acceleration">acce=
leration</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Force" title=3D"Forc=
e">force</a>, etc.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Differential_geometry">Diff=
erential geometry</h3></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Hyperbolic_triangle.svg" clas=
s=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedi=
a/commons/thumb/8/89/Hyperbolic_triangle.svg/250px-Hyperbolic_triangle.svg.=
png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"173" class=3D"mw-file-eleme=
nt" data-file-width=3D"809" data-file-height=3D"559"></a><figcaption><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Differential_geometry" title=3D"Differen=
tial geometry">Differential geometry</a> uses tools from <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus" title=3D"Calculus">calculus</a> to study p=
roblems involving curvature.</figcaption></figure>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Differential_geometr=
y" title=3D"Differential geometry">Differential geometry</a></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Differential_geometry" title=3D=
"Differential geometry">Differential geometry</a> uses techniques of <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus" title=3D"Calculus">calculus</a=
> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_algebra" title=3D"Lin=
ear algebra">linear algebra</a> to study problems in geometry.<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-Walschap2015_98-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-Walschap2015-98"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>94<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> It has applicat=
ions in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Physics" title=3D"Physics"=
>physics</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Flanders2012_99-0" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-Flanders2012-99"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>95<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Econometrics" title=3D"=
Econometrics">econometrics</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-MarriottSalmon2000_100-0=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cit=
e_note-MarriottSalmon2000-100"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>96<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Bioinformatics" title=3D"Bioinformatics">bioinformatics</a>,<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-HePetoukhov2011_101-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-HePetoukhov2011-101"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>97<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up> among others.
</p><p>In particular, differential geometry is of importance to <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_physics" title=3D"Mathematical p=
hysics">mathematical physics</a> due to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Albert_Einstein" title=3D"Albert Einstein">Albert Einstein</a>'s <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/General_relativity" title=3D"General r=
elativity">general relativity</a> postulation that the <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Universe" title=3D"Universe">universe</a> is <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Curvature" title=3D"Curvature">curved</a>=
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Dirac2016_102-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-Dirac2016-102"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>98<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Diffe=
rential geometry can either be <i>intrinsic</i> (meaning that the spaces it=
 considers are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Smooth_manifold" cl=
ass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Smooth manifold">smooth manifolds</a> whose ge=
ometric structure is governed by a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Riemannian_metric" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Riemannian metric">Riema=
nnian metric</a>, which determines how distances are measured near each poi=
nt) or <i>extrinsic</i> (where the object under study is a part of some amb=
ient flat Euclidean space).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-AyJost2017_103-0" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-AyJos=
t2017-103"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>99<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Non-Euclidean_geometry">Non=
-Euclidean geometry</h4></div>
<div class=3D"excerpt-block"><link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" hre=
f=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnot=
e navigation-not-searchable dablink excerpt-hat selfref">This section is an=
 excerpt from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Non-Euclidean_geomet=
ry" title=3D"Non-Euclidean geometry">Non-Euclidean geometry</a>.<span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-like plainlinks"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">=
[</span><a class=3D"external text" href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index=
.php?title=3DNon-Euclidean_geometry&amp;action=3Dedit">edit</a><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div><div class=3D"excerpt">
<p class=3D"mw-empty-elt">
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Noneuclid.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description">=
<img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/78/Noneu=
clid.svg/500px-Noneuclid.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"400" height=
=3D"101" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"663" data-file-height=
=3D"167"></a><figcaption><div class=3D"center">Behavior of lines with a com=
mon perpendicular in each of the three types of geometry</div></figcaption>=
</figure>
In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics" title=3D"Mathemati=
cs">mathematics</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Non-Euclidean=
_geometry" title=3D"Non-Euclidean geometry">non-Euclidean geometry</a> cons=
ists of two geometries based on <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ax=
iom" title=3D"Axiom">axioms</a> closely related to those that specify <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_geometry" title=3D"Euclidean =
geometry">Euclidean geometry</a>. As Euclidean geometry lies at the interse=
ction of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metric_geometry" class=3D=
"mw-redirect" title=3D"Metric geometry">metric geometry</a> and <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Affine_geometry" title=3D"Affine geometry">af=
fine geometry</a>, non-Euclidean geometry arises by either replacing the <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parallel_postulate" title=3D"Paralle=
l postulate">parallel postulate</a> with an alternative, or consideration o=
f <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quadratic_form" title=3D"Quadrat=
ic form">quadratic forms</a> other than the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Definite_quadratic_form" title=3D"Definite quadratic form">defini=
te quadratic forms</a> associated with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Metric_geometry" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Metric geometry">metri=
c geometry</a>. In the former case, one obtains <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Hyperbolic_geometry" title=3D"Hyperbolic geometry">hyperbolic=
 geometry</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elliptic_geometr=
y" title=3D"Elliptic geometry">elliptic geometry</a>, the traditional non-E=
uclidean geometries. When <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isotropi=
c_quadratic_form" title=3D"Isotropic quadratic form">isotropic quadratic fo=
rms</a> are admitted, then there are affine planes associated with the <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#Planar_algebras">planar algeb=
ras</a>, which give rise to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geomet=
ry#Kinematic_geometries">kinematic geometries</a> that have also been calle=
d non-Euclidean geometry.</div></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Topology">Topology</h3></di=
v>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Topology" title=3D"T=
opology">Topology</a></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Trefoil_knot_arb.png" class=
=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia=
/commons/thumb/4/46/Trefoil_knot_arb.png/250px-Trefoil_knot_arb.png" decodi=
ng=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"188" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-fi=
le-width=3D"1024" data-file-height=3D"768"></a><figcaption>A thickening of =
the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trefoil_knot" title=3D"Trefoil=
 knot">trefoil knot</a></figcaption></figure>
<p>Topology is the field concerned with the properties of <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Continuous_mapping" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"=
Continuous mapping">continuous mappings</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Crossley201=
1_104-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geome=
try#cite_note-Crossley2011-104"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>100<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and can be considered a genera=
lization of Euclidean geometry.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-NashSen1988_105-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-=
NashSen1988-105"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>101<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In practice, topology often means dealing wit=
h large-scale properties of spaces, such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Connectedness" title=3D"Connectedness">connectedness</a> and <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Compact_(topology)" class=3D"mw-redire=
ct" title=3D"Compact (topology)">compactness</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Munkre=
s_52-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geomet=
ry#cite_note-Munkres-52"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>49<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The field of topology, which saw massive development in the 20th cen=
tury, is in a technical sense a type of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Transformation_geometry" title=3D"Transformation geometry">transforma=
tion geometry</a>, in which transformations are <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Homeomorphism" title=3D"Homeomorphism">homeomorphisms</a>.<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-Martin1996_106-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-Martin1996-106"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>102<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This h=
as often been expressed in the form of the saying 'topology is rubber-sheet=
 geometry'. Subfields of topology include <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Geometric_topology" title=3D"Geometric topology">geometric topology=
</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Differential_topology" title=
=3D"Differential topology">differential topology</a>, <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebraic_topology" title=3D"Algebraic topology">algebr=
aic topology</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/General_topol=
ogy" title=3D"General topology">general topology</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Ma=
y1999_107-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/G=
eometry#cite_note-May1999-107"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>103<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Algebraic_geometry">Algebra=
ic geometry</h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebraic_geometry" =
title=3D"Algebraic geometry">Algebraic geometry</a></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Calabi_yau.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"=
><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f3/Cala=
bi_yau.jpg/250px-Calabi_yau.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D=
"261" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"1432" data-file-height=
=3D"1493"></a><figcaption>Quintic <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Calabi%E2%80%93Yau_manifold" title=3D"Calabi=E2=80=93Yau manifold">Calabi=
=E2=80=93Yau threefold</a></figcaption></figure>
<p>Algebraic geometry is fundamentally the study by means of <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebra" title=3D"Algebra">algebraic</a> methods=
 of some geometrical shapes, called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Algebraic_set" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Algebraic set">algebraic se=
ts</a>, and defined as common <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zero=
_of_a_function" title=3D"Zero of a function">zeros</a> of <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multivariate_polynomial" class=3D"mw-redirect" titl=
e=3D"Multivariate polynomial">multivariate polynomials</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-AHartshorne2013_108-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-AHartshorne2013-108"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>104<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Algebraic=
 geometry became an autonomous subfield of geometry <abbr title=3D"circa">c=
.</abbr><span style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">=E2=80=891900</span>, with a th=
eorem called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hilbert%27s_Nullstell=
ensatz" title=3D"Hilbert's Nullstellensatz">Hilbert's Nullstellensatz</a> t=
hat establishes a strong correspondence between algebraic sets and <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ideal_(ring_theory)" title=3D"Ideal (ring=
 theory)">ideals</a> of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polynomial=
_ring" title=3D"Polynomial ring">polynomial rings</a>. This led to a parall=
el development of algebraic geometry, and its algebraic counterpart, called=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Commutative_algebra" title=3D"Com=
mutative algebra">commutative algebra</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Dieudonne1985=
_109-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geomet=
ry#cite_note-Dieudonne1985-109"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>105<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> From the late 1950s through th=
e mid-1970s algebraic geometry had undergone major foundational development=
, with the introduction by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alexand=
er_Grothendieck" title=3D"Alexander Grothendieck">Alexander Grothendieck</a=
> of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scheme_theory" class=3D"mw-re=
direct" title=3D"Scheme theory">scheme theory</a>, which allows using <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebraic_topology" title=3D"Algebraic =
topology">topological methods</a>, including <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Cohomology_theory" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Cohomology the=
ory">cohomology theories</a> in a purely algebraic context.<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-Dieudonne1985_109-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-Dieudonne1985-109"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>105<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Scheme theory=
 allowed to solve many difficult problems not only in geometry, but also in=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theory" title=3D"Number th=
eory">number theory</a>. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wiles%27_=
proof_of_Fermat%27s_Last_Theorem" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Wiles' pro=
of of Fermat's Last Theorem">Wiles' proof of Fermat's Last Theorem</a> is a=
 famous example of a long-standing problem of <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Number_theory" title=3D"Number theory">number theory</a> whose =
solution uses scheme theory and its extensions such as <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stack_(mathematics)" title=3D"Stack (mathematics)">sta=
ck theory</a>. One of seven <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Millen=
nium_Prize_problems" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Millennium Prize proble=
ms">Millennium Prize problems</a>, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Hodge_conjecture" title=3D"Hodge conjecture">Hodge conjecture</a>, is =
a question in algebraic geometry.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-CarlsonCarlson2006_110=
-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#c=
ite_note-CarlsonCarlson2006-110"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>106<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Algebraic geometry has applications in many areas, including <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cryptography" title=3D"Cryptography">cryp=
tography</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-HoweLauter2017_111-0" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-HoweLauter2017-1=
11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>107<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/String_theory=
" title=3D"String theory">string theory</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-MarinoThadd=
eus2008_112-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Geometry#cite_note-MarinoThaddeus2008-112"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>108<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Complex_geometry">Complex g=
eometry</h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_geometry" ti=
tle=3D"Complex geometry">Complex geometry</a></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_geometry" title=3D"Comp=
lex geometry">Complex geometry</a> studies the nature of geometric structur=
es modelled on, or arising out of, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Complex_plane" title=3D"Complex plane">complex plane</a>.<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-113" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ge=
ometry#cite_note-113"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>109<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-114" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-114"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>110<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-115" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-115"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>111<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Complex geometry li=
es at the intersection of differential geometry, algebraic geometry, and an=
alysis of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Several_complex_variable=
s" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Several complex variables">several comple=
x variables</a>, and has found applications to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/String_theory" title=3D"String theory">string theory</a> and <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mirror_symmetry_(string_theory)" ti=
tle=3D"Mirror symmetry (string theory)">mirror symmetry</a>.<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-116" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geom=
etry#cite_note-116"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>112<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Complex geometry first appeared as a distinct area of study in the w=
ork of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bernhard_Riemann" title=3D"=
Bernhard Riemann">Bernhard Riemann</a> in his study of <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Riemann_surface" title=3D"Riemann surface">Riemann sur=
faces</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-117" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-117"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>113<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-118" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometr=
y#cite_note-118"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>114<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-119" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-119"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>115<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> Work in the spirit of Riemann was carried out by the <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Italian_school_of_algebraic_geometry" title=3D"Italian=
 school of algebraic geometry">Italian school of algebraic geometry</a> in =
the early 1900s. Contemporary treatment of complex geometry began with the =
work of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jean-Pierre_Serre" title=
=3D"Jean-Pierre Serre">Jean-Pierre Serre</a>, who introduced the concept of=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sheaf_(mathematics)" title=3D"She=
af (mathematics)">sheaves</a> to the subject, and illuminated the relations=
 between complex geometry and algebraic geometry.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-120" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_n=
ote-120"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>116<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-121" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-121"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>117<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
The primary objects of study in complex geometry are <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_manifold" title=3D"Complex manifold">complex man=
ifolds</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_algebraic_vari=
eties" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Complex algebraic varieties">complex =
algebraic varieties</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Compl=
ex_analytic_varieties" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Complex analytic vari=
eties">complex analytic varieties</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Holomorphic_vector_bundles" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Holomor=
phic vector bundles">holomorphic vector bundles</a> and <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coherent_sheaves" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Cohe=
rent sheaves">coherent sheaves</a> over these spaces. Special examples of s=
paces studied in complex geometry include Riemann surfaces, and <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calabi%E2%80%93Yau_manifold" title=3D"Calabi=
=E2=80=93Yau manifold">Calabi=E2=80=93Yau manifolds</a>, and these spaces f=
ind uses in string theory. In particular, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Worldsheet" title=3D"Worldsheet">worldsheets</a> of strings are mod=
elled by Riemann surfaces, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sup=
erstring_theory" title=3D"Superstring theory">superstring theory</a> predic=
ts that the extra 6 dimensions of 10 dimensional <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Spacetime" title=3D"Spacetime">spacetime</a> may be modelled=
 by Calabi=E2=80=93Yau manifolds.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Discrete_geometry">Discrete=
 geometry</h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Discrete_geometry" t=
itle=3D"Discrete geometry">Discrete geometry</a></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Closepacking.svg" class=3D"mw-file-descriptio=
n"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2e/Cl=
osepacking.svg/250px-Closepacking.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250"=
 height=3D"190" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"703" data-file=
-height=3D"534"></a><figcaption>Discrete geometry includes the study of var=
ious <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sphere_packing" title=3D"Sphe=
re packing">sphere packings</a>.</figcaption></figure>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Discrete_geometry" title=3D"Dis=
crete geometry">Discrete geometry</a> is a subject that has close connectio=
ns with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Convex_geometry" title=3D"=
Convex geometry">convex geometry</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Matou=C5=A1ek2013_=
122-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometr=
y#cite_note-Matou%C5%A1ek2013-122"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>118=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Zong2006=
_123-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geomet=
ry#cite_note-Zong2006-123"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>119<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Gruber2007_124-0=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cit=
e_note-Gruber2007-124"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>120<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> It is concerned mainly with questions =
of relative position of simple geometric objects, such as points, lines and=
 circles. Examples include the study of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Sphere_packing" title=3D"Sphere packing">sphere packings</a>, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Triangulation_(geometry)" title=3D"Triang=
ulation (geometry)">triangulations</a>, the Kneser-Poulsen conjecture, etc.=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-DevadossO'Rourke2011_125-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-DevadossO'Rourke2011-1=
25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>121<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Bezdek2010_126-0" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-Bezdek2010-126">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>122<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup> It shares many methods and principles with <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Combinatorics" title=3D"Combinatorics">combinatorics<=
/a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Computational_geometry">Com=
putational geometry</h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computational_geomet=
ry" title=3D"Computational geometry">Computational geometry</a></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computational_geometry" title=
=3D"Computational geometry">Computational geometry</a> deals with <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algorithm" title=3D"Algorithm">algorithms=
</a> and their <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Implementation_(com=
puter_science)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Implementation (computer sci=
ence)">implementations</a> for manipulating geometrical objects. Important =
problems historically have included the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Travelling_salesman_problem" title=3D"Travelling salesman problem">tr=
avelling salesman problem</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Min=
imum_spanning_tree" title=3D"Minimum spanning tree">minimum spanning trees<=
/a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hidden-line_removal" title=3D=
"Hidden-line removal">hidden-line removal</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Linear_programming" title=3D"Linear programming">linear pr=
ogramming</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-PreparataShamos2012_127-0" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-Preparata=
Shamos2012-127"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>123<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Although being a young area of geometry, it has many applications in=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_vision" title=3D"Compute=
r vision">computer vision</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ima=
ge_processing" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Image processing">image proce=
ssing</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer-aided_design" =
title=3D"Computer-aided design">computer-aided design</a>, <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Medical_imaging" title=3D"Medical imaging">medical=
 imaging</a>, etc.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-GuYau2008_128-0" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-GuYau2008-128">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>124<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Geometric_group_theory">Geo=
metric group theory</h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometric_group_theo=
ry" title=3D"Geometric group theory">Geometric group theory</a></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Cayley_graph_of_F2.svg" class=
=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia=
/commons/thumb/d/d2/Cayley_graph_of_F2.svg/250px-Cayley_graph_of_F2.svg.png=
" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"250" class=3D"mw-file-element"=
 data-file-width=3D"1024" data-file-height=3D"1024"></a><figcaption>The Cay=
ley graph of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Free_group" title=
=3D"Free group">free group</a> on two generators <i>a</i> and <i>b</i></fig=
caption></figure>
<p>Groups have been understood as geometric objects since <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Erlangen_program" title=3D"Erlangen program">Klein'=
s Erlangen programme</a>. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometri=
c_group_theory" title=3D"Geometric group theory">Geometric group theory</a>=
 studies <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Group_action" title=3D"Gr=
oup action">group actions</a> on objects that are regarded as geometric (si=
gnificantly, isometric actions on <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Metric_space" title=3D"Metric space">metric spaces</a>) to study <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Finitely_generated_group" title=3D"Finitely =
generated group">finitely generated groups</a>, often involving large-scale=
 geometric techniques<sup id=3D"cite_ref-L=C3=B6h2017_129-0" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-L%C3%B6h2=
017-129"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>125<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup> and borrowing from topology, geometry, dynamics and a=
nalysis.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-130" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-130"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>126<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> It had a significan=
t impact on <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Low-dimensional_topolo=
gy" title=3D"Low-dimensional topology">low-dimensional topology</a>, a cele=
brated result being Agol's proof of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Virtually_Haken_conjecture" title=3D"Virtually Haken conjecture">virt=
ually Haken conjecture</a> that combines <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Geometrization_conjecture" title=3D"Geometrization conjecture">Perel=
man geometrization</a> with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cubica=
l_complex" title=3D"Cubical complex">cubulation</a> techniques.<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-131" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/G=
eometry#cite_note-131"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>127<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Group actions on their <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cayl=
ey_graph" title=3D"Cayley graph">Cayley graphs</a> are foundational example=
s of isometric group actions. Other major topics include <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quasi-isometry" title=3D"Quasi-isometry">quasi-isome=
tries</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gromov-hyperbolic_group=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Gromov-hyperbolic group">Gromov-hyperbolic=
 groups</a> and their generalizations (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Relatively_hyperbolic_group" title=3D"Relatively hyperbolic group">rel=
atively</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Acylindrically_hyp=
erbolic_group" title=3D"Acylindrically hyperbolic group">acylindrically hyp=
erbolic groups</a>), <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Free_group" t=
itle=3D"Free group">free groups</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Out(Fn)" title=3D"Out(Fn)">their automorphisms</a>, <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bass%E2%80%93Serre_theory" title=3D"Bass=E2=80=93Se=
rre theory">groups acting on trees</a>, various notions of nonpositive curv=
ature for groups (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CAT(0)_group" ti=
tle=3D"CAT(0) group">CAT(0) groups</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Dehn_function" title=3D"Dehn function">Dehn functions</a>, <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Automatic_group" title=3D"Automatic group">a=
utomaticity</a>...), <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Right_angled_=
Artin_group" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Right angled Artin group">right=
 angled Artin groups</a>, and topics close to <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Combinatorial_group_theory" title=3D"Combinatorial group theory=
">combinatorial group theory</a> such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Small_cancellation_theory" title=3D"Small cancellation theory">small=
 cancellation theory</a> and algorithmic problems (e.g. the <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Word_problem_for_groups" title=3D"Word problem fo=
r groups">word</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conjugacy_prob=
lem" title=3D"Conjugacy problem">conjugacy</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Group_isomorphism_problem" title=3D"Group isomorphism pro=
blem">isomorphism problems</a>). Other group-theoretic topics like <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mapping_class_group_of_a_surface" title=
=3D"Mapping class group of a surface">mapping class groups</a>, <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kazhdan%27s_property_(T)" title=3D"Kazhdan's =
property (T)">property (T)</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/So=
lvable_group" title=3D"Solvable group">solvability</a>, <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amenable_group" title=3D"Amenable group">amenability<=
/a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lattice_(discrete_subgroup=
)" title=3D"Lattice (discrete subgroup)">lattices in Lie groups</a> are som=
etimes regarded as strongly geometric as well.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-L=C3=B6h2=
017_129-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geo=
metry#cite_note-L%C3%B6h2017-129"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>125<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Wise2012_=
132-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometr=
y#cite_note-Wise2012-132"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>128<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-133" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-133"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>129<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-134" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-134"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>130<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Convex_geometry">Convex geo=
metry</h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Convex_geometry" tit=
le=3D"Convex geometry">Convex geometry</a></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Convex_geometry" title=3D"Conve=
x geometry">Convex geometry</a> investigates <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Convex_set" title=3D"Convex set">convex</a> shapes in the Euclid=
ean space and its more abstract analogues, often using techniques of <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real_analysis" title=3D"Real analysis">r=
eal analysis</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Discrete_math=
ematics" title=3D"Discrete mathematics">discrete mathematics</a>.<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-Meurant2014_135-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-Meurant2014-135"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>131<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> It has clos=
e connections to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Convex_analysis" =
title=3D"Convex analysis">convex analysis</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Optimization" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Optimization">opt=
imization</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Functional_analy=
sis" title=3D"Functional analysis">functional analysis</a> and important ap=
plications in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theory" title=
=3D"Number theory">number theory</a>.
</p><p>Convex geometry dates back to antiquity.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Meurant2=
014_135-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geo=
metry#cite_note-Meurant2014-135"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>131<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Archimedes" title=3D"Archimedes">Archimedes</a> gave the first =
known precise definition of convexity. The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Isoperimetric_problem" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Isoperimetri=
c problem">isoperimetric problem</a>, a recurring concept in convex geometr=
y, was studied by the Greeks as well, including <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Zenodorus_(mathematician)" title=3D"Zenodorus (mathematician)=
">Zenodorus</a>. Archimedes, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plato=
" title=3D"Plato">Plato</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eucli=
d" title=3D"Euclid">Euclid</a>, and later <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Kepler" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Kepler">Kepler</a> and <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coxeter" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D=
"Coxeter">Coxeter</a> all studied <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Convex_polytope" title=3D"Convex polytope">convex polytopes</a> and their p=
roperties. From the 19th century on, mathematicians have studied other area=
s of convex mathematics, including higher-dimensional polytopes, volume and=
 surface area of convex bodies, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ga=
ussian_curvature" title=3D"Gaussian curvature">Gaussian curvature</a>, <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algorithms" class=3D"mw-redirect" titl=
e=3D"Algorithms">algorithms</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/T=
iling_(geometry)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Tiling (geometry)">tilings=
</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lattice_(group)" title=3D=
"Lattice (group)">lattices</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Applications">Applications<=
/h2></div>
<p>Geometry has found applications in many fields, some of which are descri=
bed below.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Art">Art</h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics_and_art"=
 title=3D"Mathematics and art">Mathematics and art</a></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Fes_Medersa_Bou_Inania_Mosaique2.jpg" class=
=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia=
/commons/thumb/b/b5/Fes_Medersa_Bou_Inania_Mosaique2.jpg/250px-Fes_Medersa_=
Bou_Inania_Mosaique2.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"333" c=
lass=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"1536" data-file-height=3D"2048"=
></a><figcaption>Bou Inania Madrasa, Fes, Morocco, zellige mosaic tiles for=
ming elaborate geometric tessellations</figcaption></figure>
<p>Mathematics and art are related in a variety of ways. For instance, the =
theory of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Perspective_(graphical)"=
 title=3D"Perspective (graphical)">perspective</a> showed that there is mor=
e to geometry than just the metric properties of figures: perspective is th=
e origin of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Projective_geometry" t=
itle=3D"Projective geometry">projective geometry</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Ri=
chter-Gebert2011_136-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-Richter-Gebert2011-136"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>132<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Artists have long used concepts of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Proportionality_(mathematics)" title=3D"Proportionality (mathematic=
s)">proportion</a> in design. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vitr=
uvius" title=3D"Vitruvius">Vitruvius</a> developed a complicated theory of =
<i>ideal proportions</i> for the human figure.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Elam2001_=
137-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometr=
y#cite_note-Elam2001-137"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>133<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> These concepts have been used and ad=
apted by artists from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michelangelo=
" title=3D"Michelangelo">Michelangelo</a> to modern comic book artists.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-Guigar2004_138-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-Guigar2004-138"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>134<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio" title=3D"=
Golden ratio">golden ratio</a> is a particular proportion that has had a co=
ntroversial role in art. Often claimed to be the most aesthetically pleasin=
g ratio of lengths, it is frequently stated to be incorporated into famous =
works of art, though the most reliable and unambiguous examples were made d=
eliberately by artists aware of this legend.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Livio2008_1=
39-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry=
#cite_note-Livio2008-139"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>135<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tiling_(geometry)" class=3D=
"mw-redirect" title=3D"Tiling (geometry)">Tilings</a>, or tessellations, ha=
ve been used in art throughout history. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Islamic_art" title=3D"Islamic art">Islamic art</a> makes frequent use=
 of tessellations, as did the art of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/M._C._Escher" title=3D"M. C. Escher">M. C. Escher</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-EmmerSchattschneider2007_140-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-EmmerSchattschneider2007-140"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>136<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup> Escher's work also made use of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Hyperbolic_geometry" title=3D"Hyperbolic geometry">hyperbolic geometry<=
/a>.
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C%C3%A9zanne" class=3D"mw-r=
edirect" title=3D"C=C3=A9zanne">C=C3=A9zanne</a> advanced the theory that a=
ll images can be built up from the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Sphere" title=3D"Sphere">sphere</a>, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Cone" title=3D"Cone">cone</a>, and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Cylinder" title=3D"Cylinder">cylinder</a>. This is still used =
in art theory today, although the exact list of shapes varies from author t=
o author.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-CapitoloSchwab2004_141-0" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-CapitoloSchwab2=
004-141"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>137<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Gelineau2011_142-0" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-Gelineau2=
011-142"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>138<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Architecture">Architecture<=
/h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main articles: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics_and_arc=
hitecture" title=3D"Mathematics and architecture">Mathematics and architect=
ure</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Architectural_geometry=
" title=3D"Architectural geometry">Architectural geometry</a></div>
<p>Geometry has many applications in architecture. In fact, it has been sai=
d that geometry lies at the core of architectural design.<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-CeccatoHesselgren2016_143-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-CeccatoHesselgren2016-143"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>139<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Pottmann2007_144-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-Pottmann2007-144"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>140<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> Applications of geometry to architecture include the use of <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Projective_geometry" title=3D"Projective geomet=
ry">projective geometry</a> to create <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Forced_perspective" title=3D"Forced perspective">forced perspective</a>=
,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-MoffettFazio2003_145-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-MoffettFazio2003-145"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>141<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup> the use of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conic_section=
" title=3D"Conic section">conic sections</a> in constructing domes and simi=
lar objects,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-HerseyHersey2001_93-1" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-HerseyHersey200=
1-93"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>89<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup> the use of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tesse=
llations" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Tessellations">tessellations</a>,<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-HerseyHersey2001_93-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-HerseyHersey2001-93"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>89<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup> and the use of symmetry.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-HerseyHersey2001_93-3" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_not=
e-HerseyHersey2001-93"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>89<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Physics">Physics</h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_physics=
" title=3D"Mathematical physics">Mathematical physics</a></div>
<p>The field of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Astronomy" title=
=3D"Astronomy">astronomy</a>, especially as it relates to mapping the posit=
ions of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Star" title=3D"Star">stars=
</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Planet" title=3D"Planet">=
planets</a> on the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Celestial_spher=
e" title=3D"Celestial sphere">celestial sphere</a> and describing the relat=
ionship between movements of celestial bodies, have served as an important =
source of geometric problems throughout history.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-GreenGr=
een1985_146-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Geometry#cite_note-GreenGreen1985-146"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>142<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Riemannian_geometry" title=
=3D"Riemannian geometry">Riemannian geometry</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Pseudo-Riemannian" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Pseudo=
-Riemannian">pseudo-Riemannian</a> geometry are used in <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/General_relativity" title=3D"General relativity">gene=
ral relativity</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Alekseevski=C4=AD2008_147-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-=
Alekseevski%C4%AD2008-147"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>143<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/String_theory" title=3D"String theory">String theory</a> makes use of=
 several variants of geometry,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-YauNadis2010_148-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-=
YauNadis2010-148"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>144<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup> as does <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Quantum_information_theory" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Quantum inf=
ormation theory">quantum information theory</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-149" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_no=
te-149"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>145<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Other_fields_of_mathematics=
">Other fields of mathematics</h3></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Square_root_of_2_triangle.svg=
" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wi=
kipedia/commons/thumb/a/a6/Square_root_of_2_triangle.svg/250px-Square_root_=
of_2_triangle.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"250" clas=
s=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"500" data-file-height=3D"500"></a>=
<figcaption>The Pythagoreans discovered that the sides of a triangle could =
have <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Commensurability_(mathematics=
)" title=3D"Commensurability (mathematics)">incommensurable</a> lengths.</f=
igcaption></figure>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus" title=3D"Calculus">Ca=
lculus</a> was strongly influenced by geometry.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Boyer201=
2_33-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geomet=
ry#cite_note-Boyer2012-33"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>30<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> For instance, the introduction of <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coordinates" class=3D"mw-redirect" t=
itle=3D"Coordinates">coordinates</a> by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Ren%C3%A9_Descartes" title=3D"Ren=C3=A9 Descartes">Ren=C3=A9 Descarte=
s</a> and the concurrent developments of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Algebra" title=3D"Algebra">algebra</a> marked a new stage for geomet=
ry, since geometric figures such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Plane_curve" title=3D"Plane curve">plane curves</a> could now be represen=
ted <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_geometry" title=3D"An=
alytic geometry">analytically</a> in the form of functions and equations. T=
his played a key role in the emergence of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Infinitesimal_calculus" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Infinitesima=
l calculus">infinitesimal calculus</a> in the 17th century. Analytic geomet=
ry continues to be a mainstay of pre-calculus and calculus curriculum.<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-FlandersPrice2014_150-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-FlandersPrice2014-150"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>146<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-RogawskiAdams2015_151-0" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-RogawskiAdams2015-15=
1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>147<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup>
</p><p>Another important area of application is <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Number_theory" title=3D"Number theory">number theory</a>.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-Lozano-Robledo2019_152-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-Lozano-Robledo2019-152"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>148<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup> In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ancient_Greece" title=
=3D"Ancient Greece">ancient Greece</a> the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Pythagoreans" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Pythagoreans">Pythago=
reans</a> considered the role of numbers in geometry. However, the discover=
y of incommensurable lengths contradicted their philosophical views.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-Sangalli2009_153-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry#cite_note-Sangalli2009-153"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>149<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Since =
the 19th century, geometry has been used for solving problems in number the=
ory, for example through the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geome=
try_of_numbers" title=3D"Geometry of numbers">geometry of numbers</a> or, m=
ore recently, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scheme_theory" class=
